ending that autism represents a queer way of being that simultaneously embraces and rejects the rhetorical, Yergeau shows how autistic people queer the lines of rhetoric, humanity, and agency. In so doing, she demonstrates how an autistic rhetoric requires the reconceptualization of rhetoric's very essence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAutism. 0aAutistic people. 0aDisability studies. 4aCCCC Book Award Winners. 4aLavender Rhetorics Book Award. 4aMLA Book Awards. 4aMLA First Book Prize Winner. 4aNCTE Award Winners. 4aRhetoric Society of America book awards. 4adisability activism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372189423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822372189.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles